## @headless/bff-nextjs

Next.js-specific BFF utilities. This package depends on `@headless/core` and `next`.

### Installation

```bash
bun add @headless/bff-nextjs
```

### createProxyHandler

Generates all HTTP method handlers for a Next.js catch-all route:

```typescript
// apps/web/src/app/api/v1/[...path]/route.ts
import { createProxyHandler } from '@headless/bff-nextjs';

export const { GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE, runtime, dynamic } =
  createProxyHandler({
    defaultBackend: 'laravel',
    backends: {
      laravel: {
        baseUrl: process.env.LARAVEL_API_URL!,
        hmac: {
          secret: process.env.BFF_SECRET!,
          bffId: process.env.BFF_ID || 'nextjs-bff',
        },
      },
      symfony: { baseUrl: process.env.SYMFONY_API_URL! },
      node: { baseUrl: process.env.HONO_API_URL! },
    },
  });
```

This single file handles all API proxying. It includes CSRF validation, HMAC signing, token refresh, and response cookie management.

### createMiddleware

Creates a Next.js middleware function for auth routing and proactive token refresh:

```typescript
// apps/web/src/middleware.ts
import { createMiddleware } from '@headless/bff-nextjs';

export default createMiddleware({
  defaultBackend: 'laravel',
  backends: { /* same as proxy config */ },
  protectedRoutes: ['/dashboard', '/admin'],
  authRoutes: ['/auth/login', '/auth/register'],
  refreshThreshold: 300, // seconds before expiry to trigger refresh
});

export const config = {
  matcher: ['/((?!_next/static|_next/image|favicon.ico).*)'],
};
```

### createBffClient

A type-safe HTTP client for use in server actions. It reads cookies from the Next.js cookie store and forwards them to the BFF proxy:

```typescript
// apps/web/src/lib/bff.ts
import { createBffClient } from '@headless/bff-nextjs';

export const bff = createBffClient({
  bffUrl: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL!,
  defaultBackend: 'laravel',
  backends: { /* same config */ },
});

// Usage in a server action:
'use server';
const user = await bff.get('/api/v1/auth/me');
await bff.post('/api/v1/auth/logout');
```

<Aside type="tip">
  Always use `createBffClient` in server actions instead of raw `fetch()`. The client handles cookie forwarding, which `credentials: 'include'` does not support in Node.js server-side contexts.
</Aside>

### createNextjsCookieStore

Wraps the Next.js `cookies()` function to implement the `CookieStore` interface:

```typescript
import { createNextjsCookieStore } from '@headless/bff-nextjs';

const cookieStore = createNextjsCookieStore();
```

